  "scrollArea": {
    "title": "Vernacular Architecture",
    "content1": "Vernacular architecture is a category of architecture based on local needs, construction materials, and reflecting local traditions.",
    "content2": "It tends to evolve over time to reflect the environmental, cultural, and historical context in which it exists.",
    "content3": "It has no architect. It is simply built by the people who will use it, using locally sourced materials and traditional techniques.",
    "content4": "The study of vernacular architecture does not examine formally schooled architects, but instead examines the work of people who learned their craft through apprenticeships and working alongside master builders.",
    "content5": "Vernacular architecture encompasses a wide range of buildings and other structures, including farmhouses, barns, sheds, stables, mills, schools, stores, churches, and other building types.",
    "content6": "Because of its functional basis, vernacular architecture tends to be simple and unadorned, relying on locally available materials and traditional construction methods."
  },
